---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Navbar from "../../components/Navbar.astro";
---

<Layout title="Device Classification">

<Navbar />

<section class="hero">

<div class="container">

<span class="badge">
Learn
</span>

<h1>Medical Device Classification</h1>

<p>

Medical devices are classified according to the potential risk posed
to patients and users. Different countries use different classification
systems, but the basic principle remains the same:
higher risk requires higher regulatory control.

</p>

<div class="buttons">

<a href="/learn/medical-device-basics" class="secondary">
← Previous
</a>

<a href="/learn/risk-management" class="primary">
Next →
</a>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Why Classification is Important?</h2>

<p>

Medical Device Classification determines the regulatory pathway,
documentation requirements, clinical evidence,
testing requirements and approval process before a product
can enter the market.

A simple thermometer follows a different approval pathway
than a heart valve or implantable pacemaker.

</p>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Indian Medical Device Classification (CDSCO)</h2>

<table>

<tr>

<th>Class</th>

<th>Risk</th>

<th>Examples</th>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>A</td>

<td>Low Risk</td>

<td>Bandage, Surgical Gloves, Tongue Depressor</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>B</td>

<td>Low Moderate Risk</td>

<td>Hypodermic Needle, Suction Equipment, Infusion Pump</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>C</td>

<td>Moderate High Risk</td>

<td>Bone Plates, Ventilator, Dialysis Machine</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>D</td>

<td>High Risk</td>

<td>Heart Valve, Pacemaker, Drug Eluting Stent</td>

</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>European Union Classification (EU MDR)</h2>

<table>

<tr>

<th>Class</th>

<th>Risk</th>

<th>Examples</th>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>I</td>

<td>Low Risk</td>

<td>Wheelchair, Hospital Bed</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>IIa</td>

<td>Medium Risk</td>

<td>Dental Filling Material, Hearing Aid</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>IIb</td>

<td>Medium High Risk</td>

<td>Ventilator, Infusion Pump</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>III</td>

<td>Highest Risk</td>

<td>Hip Implant, Knee Implant, Pacemaker</td>

</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>US FDA Classification</h2>

<table>

<tr>

<th>FDA Class</th>

<th>Description</th>

<th>Examples</th>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Class I</td>

<td>General Controls</td>

<td>Elastic Bandage</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Class II</td>

<td>General + Special Controls</td>

<td>Infusion Pump</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Class III</td>

<td>Premarket Approval Required</td>

<td>Heart Valve, Pacemaker</td>

</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>
<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Classification Rules</h2>

<p>

Medical devices are classified using internationally accepted rules
based on the intended purpose of the device, duration of contact,
degree of invasiveness, whether the device is active or non-active,
implantability, and the part of the human body affected.

</p>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>🩹 Non-Invasive Devices</h3>

<p>

Devices that do not penetrate the body.

</p>

<ul>

<li>Hospital Beds</li>

<li>Wheelchairs</li>

<li>Bandages</li>

<li>Surgical Masks</li>

<li>External Supports</li>

</ul>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>💉 Invasive Devices</h3>

<p>

Devices entering the human body through natural openings or surgery.

</p>

<ul>

<li>Catheters</li>

<li>Needles</li>

<li>Endoscopes</li>

<li>Surgical Instruments</li>

<li>Bone Screws</li>

</ul>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>⚡ Active Devices</h3>

<p>

Devices requiring electrical or other energy sources.

</p>

<ul>

<li>ECG Machine</li>

<li>Ventilator</li>

<li>MRI Scanner</li>

<li>Defibrillator</li>

<li>Infusion Pump</li>

</ul>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>🦴 Implantable Devices</h3>

<p>

Devices intended to remain inside the body.

</p>

<ul>

<li>Hip Implant</li>

<li>Knee Implant</li>

<li>Dental Implant</li>

<li>Heart Valve</li>

<li>Pacemaker</li>

</ul>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Software as a Medical Device (SaMD)</h2>

<p>

Software intended for diagnosis, monitoring or treatment without being
part of a hardware medical device is known as Software as a Medical
Device (SaMD). Examples include AI diagnostic software, ECG analysis
applications and radiology image analysis software.

</p>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Typical Classification Examples</h2>

<table>

<tr>

<th>Device</th>

<th>India</th>

<th>EU</th>

<th>FDA</th>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Thermometer</td>

<td>A</td>

<td>I</td>

<td>I</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Infusion Pump</td>

<td>B</td>

<td>IIb</td>

<td>II</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Ventilator</td>

<td>C</td>

<td>IIb</td>

<td>II</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Total Hip Implant</td>

<td>C</td>

<td>III</td>

<td>II</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Pacemaker</td>

<td>D</td>

<td>III</td>

<td>III</td>

</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Regulatory Approval Pathway</h2>

<div class="timeline">

<div class="step">
Device Idea
</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">
Classification
</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">
Risk Assessment
</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">
Testing
</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">
Clinical Evidence
</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">
Regulatory Submission
</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">
Approval
</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">
Post Market Surveillance
</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Quick Facts</h2>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>Class A / Class I</h3>

<p>

Low-risk devices with simpler regulatory requirements.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Class B / IIa</h3>

<p>

Moderate-risk devices requiring additional technical documentation.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Class C / IIb</h3>

<p>

Higher-risk devices with greater clinical and regulatory requirements.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Class D / III</h3>

<p>

Highest-risk implantable and life-supporting devices requiring extensive
clinical evidence.

</p>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>
<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Orthopedic Device Classification Examples</h2>

<table>

<tr>

<th>Device</th>

<th>Typical Risk</th>

<th>Reason</th>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Total Hip Replacement</td>

<td>High</td>

<td>Permanent implant with long-term body contact</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Total Knee Replacement</td>

<td>High</td>

<td>Permanent implant requiring clinical evidence</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Bone Plate</td>

<td>Moderate–High</td>

<td>Internal fixation device</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Bone Screw</td>

<td>Moderate–High</td>

<td>Implantable fixation device</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td>Spinal Implant</td>

<td>High</td>

<td>Critical implantable medical device</td>

</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Classification of In Vitro Diagnostic (IVD) Devices</h2>

<p>

IVDs are medical devices used for the examination of specimens such as
blood, urine, tissue, or other body fluids to provide information about
a patient's health condition.

</p>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>Low Risk</h3>

<p>

General laboratory reagents and instruments.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Moderate Risk</h3>

<p>

Routine clinical chemistry and hematology assays.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>High Risk</h3>

<p>

Blood screening tests, HIV diagnostics and infectious disease testing.

</p>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>Why is classification important?</h3>

<p>

Classification determines the regulatory pathway, testing,
documentation and approval requirements.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Who performs device classification?</h3>

<p>

Manufacturers classify devices according to regulatory rules, while
regulatory authorities verify the classification during review.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Can the same device have different classes?</h3>

<p>

Yes. Classification may vary slightly between India, the EU and the USA
because each region follows its own regulations.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Which factors influence classification?</h3>

<p>

Duration of contact, invasiveness, intended purpose, active/non-active
nature, implantability and patient risk.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>What happens if a device is misclassified?</h3>

<p>

Incorrect classification may lead to rejection of regulatory
submissions, delays in approval or compliance issues.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Where can I verify the classification?</h3>

<p>

Always refer to the applicable regulations and official guidance issued
by CDSCO, FDA or the European Commission.

</p>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

